<HEADLINE>
<P>
THE NATION 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Many Americans remain fat because they refuse to exercise while they diet, 
according to the Centers for Disease Control. CDC researchers reported that 
43.6% of overweight men and 63.9% of women tried to lose weight only by eating 
fewer calories, and 24.3% of heavy men and 34.7% of the overweight women 
increased their physical activity but did not diet. "We need to incorporate 
physical activity along with caloric restriction," said Eddas M. Bennett, a CDC 
epidemiologist. "One is not better without the other. You really need both." 
The CDC survey found that 34 million Americans -- about one in four adults -- 
are overweight by 20% or more. Bennett blamed the unwillingness to exercise on 
the preoccupation with fad diets and a "more sedentary" life style. 
</P>
</TEXT>
