<HEADLINE>
<P>
MORNING REPORT: TV &amp; VIDEO 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By ALEENE MacMINN, Arts and entertainment reports from The Times, national and 
international news services and the nation's press. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Roasted by critics for its news re-creations, NBC News' "Yesterday, Today and 
Tomorrow" won its time period in its debut Wednesday night, according to 
NBC-provided estimates. Facing only reruns, "Yesterday" averaged a 12.0 
overnight rating and a 23% share of audience. ABC's "China Beach" had an 8.2 
and a 16 share, while CBS's "Wiseguy" had a 7.1 and 14% share. Each ratings 
point represents 904,000 homes. "Yesterday" has two more shows (on Aug. 23 and 
Sept. 13), after which NBC will look at the ratings and decide whether it will 
become a series, a spokesman said Thursday. ALEENE MacMINN 
</P>
</TEXT>
