<HEADLINE>
<P>
FIRST IMPRESSIONS: RECOMMENDATION FOR EL TORITO GRILL -- WITH RESERVATIONS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By RUTH REICHL 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
You should probably know that although they will gladly take your reservation 
when you call, and although the sign at the desk loudly proclaims "reservations 
taken," they do not really take reservations at the new El Torito Grill, 9595 
Wilshire Blvd., Beverly Hills, (213) 550-1599. What they do is put you at the 
head of the waiting list when you arrive. And although the restaurant has been 
open barely a week, is the size of a small airport and is densely filled with 
tables, that list is bound to be sizable by the time you get there. Already the 
place is packed. 
</P>
<P>
When you finally get a table you will discover that it is in a room so loud 
that you won't be able to hear the baby at the next table crying. Once the 
waiter has brought exotic drinks like Pink Cadillac Margaritas and mixed 
guacamole at your table, you may not care. So you'll go on to various 
combinations of tacos, taquitos, enchiladas and the like (all very reasonably 
priced), or a rather ornate series of Southwestern specials. "It's a Hasidic 
quesadilla," a man at one table was saying as we passed, contemplating a 
concoction filled with smoked salmon, jicama, apples and toasted pinenuts with 
cilantro and green chile pesto. 
</P>
<P>
As for dessert -- are you ready for banana-filled chocolate enchiladas? RUTH 
REICHL 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, El Torito Grill in Beverly Hills is doing brisk business after barely a 
week in operation. PATRICK DOWNS / Los Angeles Times 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
