</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times wire services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
CHARLESTON, W.Va. 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A judge today upheld a West Virginia law that allows the state to revoke the 
driver's licenses of school dropouts, a law used as a model for pending federal 
legislation. 
</P>
<P>
Kanawha County Circuit Judge Paul Zakaib said the law is based on the state's 
interest in keeping teen-agers in school, "is not unreasonable and withstands 
any constitutional challenge." 
</P>
<P>
The case involved an appeal filed by Michael Means, 17, of Charleston, who lost 
his license after he dropped out of junior high one month after his 16th 
birthday. Means, whose 16-year-old wife is expecting their first child this 
month, says he cannot get a job to support his family without driving 
privileges. 
</P>
