BRITAIN GRANTS 3 CHINESE DIPLOMATS ASYLUM, WEIGHS ANOTHER'S REQUEST 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times wire services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
LONDON 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Britain has granted political asylum to three Chinese diplomats and is 
considering an application from a fourth, the Home Office said today. 
</P>
<P>
The four sought asylum after the Chinese government's military crackdown on 
pro-democracy protesters in Beijing in early June. 
</P>
<P>
Two of those granted asylum were first secretaries in the science and 
technology section of the Chinese Embassy in London. They were not named. 
</P>
<P>
The third was Ning Hongshan, a second secretary in the education section who 
walked into a police station in London's West End in June and asked to stay in 
Britain. 
</P>
<P>
The fourth diplomat, whose name was not disclosed, was a middle-ranking 
official, a Home Office spokesman said. 
</P>
<P>
At least 20 Chinese diplomats in Western countries have defected since tanks 
and troops ended the demonstrations in Beijing's Tian An Men Square on June 4. 
</P>
