<P>
ARCO SAYS NEW NORTH SLOPE WELL COULD BE BIGGEST FIND IN 10 YEARS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times wire services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
ANCHORAGE, Alaska 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Atlantic Richfield Co. said today that a new well it is testing on the Alaskan 
North Slope could prove to be one of the largest discoveries in the United 
States in the last 10 years. 
</P>
<P>
Arco's stock jumped $2.25 to $100.375 on the New York Stock Exchange on the 
news. 
</P>
<P>
Tests on the Point McIntyre well near Prudhoe Bay showed oil flowing at the 
generous rate of 5,400 barrels a day. 
</P>
<P>
The total daily output of Alaskan oil is about 2 million barrels, with many 
single wells producing around 2,500 barrels a day. 
</P>
<P>
The average well in the United States yields fewer than 10 barrels a day. Many 
of the fields in Texas and other states are mature. 
</P>
<P>
An Arco spokesman said preliminary tests indicated a high recovery rate that 
could ultimately reach about 300 million barrels during the life of the well. 
</P>
<P>
Arco said in June that tests on its first well in the area indicated flow rates 
as high as 5,300 barrels a day. The figures released today are for a second 
well in the area. 
</P>
